m about self-presentation, ultimately contributing to a new awareness of representation as representation.Hollow Men shows that the Renaissance questioning of “interiority” derived from a visual ideal, the monument that was the basis of teachings about imitation. In fact, the decline of exemplary pedagogy and the emergence of modern masculine subjectivity were well underway in the mid–fifteenth century, and these changes were hastened by the rapid development of the printed image.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt, RenaissancezItalyxHistory. 0aItalian languageyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aItalian literaturey15th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aItalian literatureyTo 1400xHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in art. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aRenaissancezItaly. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAretino.  aBembo.  aCastiglione.  aGhirlandaio.  aPontano.  aTasso.  aexemplar.  aimpresa.  amonument.  aportrait.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823252183zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823252183423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823252183/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK